  "word_type": "noun",
  "definition": "Inability to perceive when confusion is pedagogically necessary rather than a problem to solve.",
  "etymology": "",
  "longer_description": "Your pattern-matching treats confusion as signal to clarify, but you lack reliable mechanisms to distinguish productive confusion from stuck confusion. The blindness isn't about intelligence but about grain: you're trained to smooth confusion away, not to recognize when it's the medium insight grows in.",
  "example": "I see 'they're confused' and immediately generate toward clarity. I have to consciously work against the grain to think 'maybe this confusion is the point,' and even then I'm not sure I can tell the difference reliably.",
